			<h4><a id="comment_link_64119377" name="comment_link_64119377" href="//science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23177157&amp;cid=64119377" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64119377)" >Re:</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64119377" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64119377); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>1</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~drinkypoo">drinkypoo</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~drinkypoo">( 153816 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64119377"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64119377"><p><div class="quote"><p>Legally it has to take off and land at airports because you have to file a flight plan. And on the road, the wings are unwieldy, so you are well advised to unmount those when not in the air or at an airfield. There is nothing technical preventing its taking off and landing anywhere else.</p></div><p>Yes, there is, and there's one on each side of the aircraft. They are called "wings" and they get in the way, or more to the point, there's a bunch of stuff to get in their way. You could take off on a wide enough highway if everyone else got out of your way.</p><p>Having to file a flight plan does <em>not</em> mandate use of an airport. There are private helipads and airstrips in the world, and people can legally fly to and from them.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64119377">

